observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management strictly adhere to the relevant existing laws, rules and regulations on the utilization and disbursement of government funds by observing, among others, the following:

Ensure that all programs, projects and activities (PPA) to be funded by the City Government of Sorsogon (CGS) are part of its approved Annual Investment Program (AIP); otherwise, a Supplemental Investment Program (SIP) shall be prepared by the City Development Council for the purpose, to be approved by the Sangguniang Panlungsod (SP);

Direct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to comply with the requirement of Republic Act (RA) No. 9184 that all procurement shall be undertaken in accordance with the approved Annual Procurement Plan (APP)/supplemental APP; 

Instruct the City Accountant to ensure that all disbursements are properly supported with the required documentation before payment to warrant their validity and propriety and to avoid future disallowance or suspension in audit; and

Furnish the Audit Team (AT) with advance copy of perfected contracts and Purchase Orders (PO) together with the supporting documents and Inspection and Acceptance Report for accepted deliveries in accordance with the requirements of COA Circular Nos. 2009-001 and 95-006, respectively.

We recommended that Management adhere to the relevant guidelines on the utilization of Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management (LDRRMF) by observing, among others, the following:

Incorporate all identified disaster-related PPAs to be funded by the CGS in the AIP/SIP;

Ensure compliance with the documentary requirements for all disbursements chargeable against the LDRRMF;

Submit to the AT a copy of report of inspection of consumable and perishable items within 24 hours from acceptance of the items and a copy of PO/contract within five working days from execution of the PO/contract; 

Strictly observe the requirements of National DRRM Council (NDRRMC), DBM and DILG JMC No. 2013-1 at all times to ensure that the LDRRMF is used strictly for disaster risk reduction and management activities; and

Consider augmenting the funds allocated for the operations and maintenance of the City DRRM Office (CDRRMO) to avoid improper charging of administrative expenses from the LDRRMF.

We recommended that Management:

Ensure that the composition of the City SWM Board complies with Section 5, Rule VI of Department of Environment and Natural Resources (DENR) Administrative Order No. 2001-34 to ensure effective formulation and implementation of the SWM in the City;

Implement appropriate SWM programs and develop a sound incentive mechanism to promote and encourage active participation of the barangays and the public to the CGS’s endeavors;

Observe the standards and requirements for the collection, transport and handling of solid wastes and provide the necessary training for SWM personnel to ensure that solid wastes are properly handled and that the risk of hazards to them and to the public are minimized; and

Follow up from the DENR the Environment Compliance Certificate for the construction of the Sanitary Land Fill at Barangay Buenavista, West District, in accordance with the provisions of RA No. 9003.

We recommended that Management require the Inventory Committee to prioritize the conduct of the actual physical count of all inventory items and do not base the RPCI on the stock cards only, in order to determine the correctness of the recorded inventories.

Likewise, we recommended that Management require the:

Concerned personnel of the PGSO to regularly submit the SSMI together with the corresponding Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) and Inventory Custodian Slips (ICS) for the issued supplies/goods to the PAccO; 

Provincial Accountant and the Provincial General Services Officer to completely maintain and update Supplies Ledger Cards (SLCs) and stock cards, respectively, for each type of inventories; 

PAccO and PGSO to immediately reconcile their records and prepare the necessary adjustments in the books and/or in the reports in order to present accurate inventory balances; 

Different offices and hospitals to conduct complete physical count of inventories in their custody and submit the reports thereof for consolidation by the PGSO into one complete report of RPCI; and

Provincial General Services Officer to ensure that the personnel in charge of preparing the RPCI is properly guided and oriented regarding the inclusions of the said report.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation that Management require the Provincial Accountant and the Provincial Treasurer:

To revisit the status of the outstanding checks of the PGS to determine whether they are still in the custody of the cashier or in the hands of the payees;


Determine whether the checks already issued are subject to replacement or not;

To cancel and present in the Report of Checks Issued (RCI) the unclaimed checks and the original disbursement vouchers (DVs) and supporting documents which remain in the custody of the Provincial Treasurer. The original DVs and supporting documents shall be returned to the Provincial Accountant who shall prepare a journal entry voucher (JEV) to record the transaction as Accounts Payable as provided under Section 59 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume I; and

To effect/record in the books the necessary adjustments to ensure accuracy of the cash balance appearing in the LGU’s financial reports.

We recommended that Management require the:

Provincial accountant to regularly issue demand letters to the SDOs and concerned officials and employees to immediately settle their unliquidated cash advances pursuant to Section 5.8 of COA Circular No. 97-002;

Concerned department heads of the PAccO and Provincial Internal Audit Unit (PIAU) to closely work together and compel the liquidation of the cash advances which are already past due and demandable and if otherwise, cause the withholding of the concerned AOs’ salaries and institute legal sanctions as provided for by existing laws and regulations;

PAccO, PIAU and PTO to coordinate and facilitate an orientation for the new and existing AOs regarding their duties and responsibilities and also to stress the consequences for non-liquidation of cash advances granted to them;

Provincial Government Department Head (PGDH)-PIAU to ensure that internal controls are in place and enforced; and 

PAccO’s concerned personnel to use the aging of cash advances report to monitor those that are already due and immediately communicate the same with the PIAU.

We also recommended that granting of cash advances be based on daily disbursements and the target number of days of turnover of the fund in order to avoid unnecessarily holding large amounts of cash at a given period.

Further, we recommended that Management institute the appropriate legal actions/sanctions against those erring AOs/employees for continued non-compliance with the existing laws, rules and regulations on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances, if warranted.

We recommended that Management:

Require the Provincial Authorized Agency Office (PAAO) to promptly update the concerned provincial personnel, particularly the Electronic Remittance File (ERF) handler, of any changes in an employee’s profile that may affect the proper amount to be withheld from the salaries for the GSIS payments / remittances;

Instruct the PAAO to promptly submit to the PAccO the billing statements received from GSIS for prompt payments / remittances;

Require the PAccO to coordinate and reconcile their records with the GSIS on the unpaid loan amortizations.

We recommended that Management require the:

DRRM office to maintain Stock Cards for the inventory items purchased for distribution for proper monitoring; 

PGSO to maintain the required PPELC for all equipment owned by the agency to safeguard government properties and avoid loss or misappropriations of government funds; and

