Consider augmenting the funds allocated for the operations and maintenance of the CDRRMO to avoid improper charging of administrative expenses from the LDRRMF.

We recommended that Management:

Secure and retain copies of the MOA on fund transfers from the SAs in order to ensure strict adherence to the specific provisions embodied therein and effective and efficient implementation of all undertakings;

Fast track and closely monitor the implementation of the projects duly supported with monitoring reports related to fund transfers since the resources are readily available, and in order not to deprive the general public of the benefits that could be derived therefrom;

Submit the liquidation reports promptly to SAs in accordance with the terms and conditions stipulated in the MOA or the provisions under COA Circular No. 94-013, in case no specific reportorial requirements are provided in the MOA; and

Prepare an adjusting entry to transfer the balance of the fund transfer from Early Childhood Care and Development Council from the Trust Liability account to the Due to NGAs account.

We recommended that Management:

Follow up the schedule of the panel interviews by the NSWMC for the deliberation and approval of the 10-year City SWM Plan that will serve as a guide for the long-term management of solid waste generated within the City’s jurisdiction;

Ensure that the composition of the City SWM Board complies with Section 5, Rule VI of Department of Environment and Natural Resources (DENR) AO No. 2001-34 to ensure effective formulation and implementation of the SWM in the City;

Implement appropriate SWM programs and develop a sound incentive mechanism to promote and encourage active participation of the barangays and the public to the City Government’s endeavors;

Observe the standards and requirements for the collection, transport and handling of solid wastes and provide the necessary training for SWM personnel to ensure that solid wastes are properly handled and that the risk of hazards to them and to the public are minimized; and

Follow up from the DENR the Environment Compliance Certificate (ECC) for the construction of the Sanitary Land Fill (SLF) at Barangay Buenavista, West District, in accordance with the provisions of RA No. 9003.

We recommended that Management:

Follow up the approval of the 10-year City SWM Plan that will serve as a guide for the long-term management of solid waste generated within the City’s jurisdiction;

Strictly comply with the requirements of RA No. 9003 particularly on the efficient collection, proper transfer and transport of wastes; and efficient management of residuals and of final disposal sites and/or any other related technologies for the destruction/reuse of residuals;

Encourage the remaining 37 barangays to establish their own Materials Recovery Facilities (MRFs) for the collection, segregation, recycling of biodegradable, recyclable, compostable and reusable wastes; and

Provide adequate assistance in restoring the four not functional barangay MRFs in the West District to functional status.

We recommended that Management strictly comply with Department of Budget and Management and DILG JMC No. 2017-1, by taking into consideration the following: 

Develop a concrete plan that will articulate the PPA, timeline, expected deliverables for each phase, key milestones, etc.; 

Adopt strategies to maximize the utilization of the 20 per cent Development Fund and implement the PPAs within the targeted timeframe to achieve the social, economic and environmental outcomes essential in the attainment of the constitutional objective of a desired quality of life for all; 

Require the Head of the Barangay Affairs Development Program Section to submit periodically the status report on the Barangay Development Program (BDP) PPAs to the City Engineer and the City Planning and Development Coordinator (CPDC) for inclusion in the Program and Project Status Report and quarterly Project Monitoring Reports, respectively; and

Strengthen the management of reporting information by improving on its monitoring and evaluation capabilities and coordination among offices with the end view of producing more complete and accurate reports that are relevant in decision-making.

