We recommended that Management:

Direct the City Accountant to properly account for all the land properties of the City Government using the cost or fair value and effect the necessary adjustments in the books to arrive at a more reliable Land account balance in the financial statements (FS);

Require the City General Services Officer and the City Assessor to exert effort in the retrieval of land titles and other necessary documents as basis to establish ownership and determine proper valuation;

Allocate adequate budget for the titling of the subject land properties in the name of the City Government to establish absolute ownership and reduce the risk of third party claims; and

Conduct proper evaluation of the 198 RPUs to facilitate the immediate recognition as assets of the City Government considering the criteria provided under Philippine Public Sector Accounting Standard (PPSAS) 17.

We recommended that Management:

Require the City General Services Office (CGSO) and the City Accounting Office to prioritize the reconciliation process and ensure that discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted in the books accordingly;

Create an Inventory Committee that will conduct an annual physical inventory of all properties of the City and prepare and submit the corresponding RPCPPE to the Audit Team within the prescribed period;

Require the City Accounting Office to maintain complete and updated PPE Ledger Cards (PPELCs) to support GL account balances and the CGSO to keep corresponding Property Cards (PCs) for control purposes; and

Compel the City Engineering Office (CEO) to provide the City Accountant and the City General Services Officer with complete description and cost of road network projects to facilitate the preparation of Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network.

We recommended that Management:

Fully investigate the unreconciled balances of the Due from Local Government Units (LGUs) account and prepare the necessary adjustments to reconcile the City Accounting Office and barangay records. Thereafter, a periodic reconciliation of both records shall be made;

Require the liquidation of financial assistance granted to the barangays in compliance with the provisions of the MOA by demanding submission of liquidation reports duly signed by the Barangay Treasurer and the Punong Barangay and supported with complete documentation per COA Circular No. 2012-001;

Demand the return of unexpended balances of financial assistance if the project has already been completed/fully implemented; or refund if unutilized or has not been used in accordance with the MOA;

Require the barangays to submit an approved Program of Works and other documentary requirements before the release of financial assistance;

Refrain from granting additional financial assistance to the barangays unless the previous financial assistance has been liquidated and the required liquidation report has been submitted; and

In the future, instruct the concerned officials to ensure that all salient provisions are incorporated in the MOA for all undertakings for an effective and efficient implementation of the same, taking into consideration the deficiencies noted in audit.

We recommended that Management:

Follow up the approval of the 10-year City Solid Waste Management (SWM) Plan that will serve as a guide for the long-term management of solid waste generated within the City’s jurisdiction;

Strictly comply with the requirements of RA No. 9003 particularly on the efficient collection, proper transfer and transport of wastes; and efficient management of residuals and of final disposal sites and/or any other related technologies for the destruction/reuse of residuals;

Prioritize SWM programs and projects by providing/allocating enough budget for their full implementation to address all the identified key issues as discussed in the City SWM plan;

Encourage the remaining 37 barangays to establish their own Materials Recovery Facilities (MRFs) for the collection, segregation, recycling of biodegradable, recyclable, compostable and reusable wastes; and

Provide adequate assistance in restoring the four not functional barangay MRFs in the West District to functional status.

We further recommended that Management conduct proper evaluation of all garbage truck units to determine their road worthiness. Otherwise, gradual phase out of the aging trucks be considered by Management to avoid the incurrence of unreasonable costs of repairs and maintenance.

We recommended that Management require:

The CGSO to observe the proper inventory and monitoring of all procured relief goods taking into consideration the Relief Distribution Sheet (RDS) evidencing the issuance to the end-users/beneficiaries and not merely the Requisition and Issue Slip drawn by the office having custody of the goods, as basis for recording in the Report of Supplies and Materials Issued (RSMI) submitted to the City Accounting Office;

The City Accounting Office to properly account for the receipt and issuance of relief goods based on PPSAS 12, Inventories, and make the necessary adjustments to reflect the correct balance of affected inventory and expense accounts;

The City Social Welfare and Development Office to be in the frontline of service delivery during and in the aftermath of man-made and natural disasters and calamities, particularly in the disposition and utilization of relief goods; and

The City Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Office (CDRRMO) to submit immediately the duly accomplished RDS as supporting document for the relief goods distributed prior to Typhoon Usman, otherwise, the undocumented distribution shall be suspended or disallowed in audit.

