We reiterated our prior years’ audit recommendations that the City Government:
Require the concerned officers and employees to liquidate/settle immediately their outstanding cash advances by demanding the immediate submission of duly accomplished liquidation reports. Otherwise, withhold any money due them;
Strengthen the operation of preventive and monitoring controls to ensure timely submission of liquidation documents and full accounting of balances of cash advances by monitoring strictly the period of liquidating cash advances;
Exert extra effort to locate the whereabouts of separated accountable officers and issue final demand letters; and
Strictly comply with the provision of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances.
We likewise recommended that Management require the City Accountant to trace the entries made that resulted in the negative balances of the cash advance balances and effect the necessary adjusting entries in the agency books in order to present the correct amount of the cash advances accounts in the financial statements; and make appropriate action to those who did not liquidate their cash advances within the prescribed period or render account of their accountabilities after demand pursuant to CSC Memorandum Circular No. 12, s. 2012.

We recommended that Management:
Provide justifications on the necessity of hiring numerous JOs in CY 2017, otherwise a Notice of Disallowance shall be issued to the City Government of Sorsogon;
Immediately require the City Human Resource Management Office (CHRMO) to formulate a Human Resource Plan and issue a uniform policy guideline on the hiring of Job Order personnel to appropriately determine the necessity of hiring JOs and to strengthen internal controls pertaining thereto;
Reduce/limit hiring of JOs and fill-up vacant positions, evaluate and determine the appropriate personnel complement of each office and effect amendments in their respective plantilla, if warranted; and
Indicate in the JO contract the specific duties of each JO personnel including the specific barangay or street (if applicable) where assigned in order to determine the scope of work and differentiate/segregate duties and functions.

We recommended that Management require the:
City Market Supervisor to employ strategies to maximize the lease of vacant stalls;
Office of the City Treasurer to update the records of the individual stallholder daily or at least weekly to monitor the status of collection;
Office of the City Treasurer to send demand letters to intensify collection of delinquent market fees to generate additional income for development projects and to improve its collection efficiency; and
Offices of the Market Supervisor and City Treasurer to coordinate with each other and strictly comply with the provisions of the Sorsogon City Market Code of 2009.
We likewise recommended that Management revisit the Sorsogon City Market Code of 2009 and review its provisions, if there is a need to amend some policies, it can be forwarded to the Sangguniang Panlungsod for legislation.

We reiterated our prior year’s audit recommendation that Management require the CGSO to facilitate the immediate disposal of the aforementioned unserviceable properties and waste materials to recoup any salvage value thereof. Specifically, we recommended the following measures:
Conduct an appraisal of the unserviceable properties and waste materials and furnish the auditor a copy of the appraisal report thereof;
Dispose the unserviceable properties based on the most appropriate mode of disposal pursuant to the provisions of COA Circular No. 92-386.

We recommended that Management require the CHRMO to: 

a. formulate plan and issue policy guidelines on the hiring of casuals/contractual/job order personnel in accordance with Section 2, Rule XI of CSC Memorandum Circular No. 40, series of 1998, COA Rules and regulations and existing labor and tax laws to strengthen internal controls pertaining thereto;

b. include in the job order contracts the job descriptions which are specific in nature as to the duties and responsibilities, targeted quantity of work to be done during the contract period, particular office to be assigned and an attestation on the part of the person to be hired that he/she is not related within the fourth degree of consanguinity or affinity with the contracting officer and the appointing authority of the City Government in compliance with Memorandum Circular No. 24, series of 2002;

c. Reduce/limit hiring of Job Orders and fill-up vacant positions; Determine and plan further on how to achieve an ideal and realistic personnel complement of the City; Conduct regular spot check in the barangays to ensure that controls such as proper recording of attendance are being implemented in the offices outside of the City Hall compound; and Evaluate the performance of employees working as JOs for more than 10 years that may be hired as a casual employee charged to the PS Budget especially those performing essential and necessary services of a regular staff or fill up vacant positions considering the ability of the City to appropriate items in the PS without exceeding the PS limitation.

We also recommended that Management require the City Accountant, CHRMO and the department heads concerned to see to it that all payrolls for the wages of job order personnel be adequately supported by:

1. Properly filled-up accomplishment reports.
2. Daily Time Report (DTR);
3. For those assigned in the field, office orders and certificate of appearances must be attached, in accordance with Section 4(6) of P.D. 1445 stating that all claims against government funds shall be supported with complete documentation.
4. A certification by the Local Chief Executive/CHRMO that the activities/services cannot be provided by regular or permanent personnel of the City.

We recommended that Management:

a. CGSO to receive and inspect all delivered relief goods and supplies; 

b. CGSO to include inventory of all the relief goods and CDRRMO supplies during the conduct physical count and submit the RSMI to the Accounting Office on a monthly basis; 

c. CGSO to maintain Property and Stock Cards, Accounting Unit to prepare and maintain PPE and Supplies Ledger Cards and regularly update their records of inventory; 

d. Accounting Unit to make necessary adjustments for the undistributed relief goods and supplies.

We recommended that Management:

1. comply with the deadlines in the submission of the Annual GAD Plan and Budget (GPB) in accordance with GPB Calendar set forth in PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01;

2. require the GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) to submit the LGU GPB to the DILG Regional Office for review and approval to ensure that the programs/projects/activities reflected thereat are in accordance with existing rules and regulations;

3. compel the GFPS to prepare that GAD Plan and Budget following the prescribed format and to follow the guidelines set forth in Annex E of the PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01;

4. direct all concerned Punong Barangays to established immediately an active VAW’s Desk in their respective barangays manned with competent personnel; and

5. instruct the City Planning and Development Office to spearhead the setting up maintenance of a GAD database to serve to serve as basis for gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation

Likewise, we recommended that coordination with other concerned departments/offices must be observed to have consolidated reports.
